90.4587, 93.6004, 93.4195, 93.5724, 94.8136, 96.7906, 97.4262, 94.8538, 92.6804, 91.1069, 89.0684, 88.2505, 89.3428, 89.1295, 90.5975, 91.2679, 92.8712, 92.188, 91.2563, 90.1059, 91.9947, 90.2123, 88.5473, 89.8275, 89.8441, 90.6462, 91.2132, 91.4431, 89.6481, 89.7864, 90.6427, 91.6811, 91.18, 90.8389, 90.7911, 93.4973, 95.2326, 95.9165, 97.1108, 95.1264, 93.5612, 94.9902, 94.1162, 93.3778, 94.2994, 95.6169, 96.7504, 97.6558, 97.6411, 100.635, 99.7746, 100.9214, 100.9899, 100.2401, 102.4978, 103.3204, 103.4037, 105.3354, 103.6593, 106.8001, 105.4105, 104.5083, 104.5297, 104.2786, 103.7662, 103.5505, 101.9671, 103.0737, 101.576, 98.8071, 98.3934, 98.5223, 98.4635, 99.0522, 99.775, 102.1478, 101.3581], "summary_html": "<h1>Time-varying Aggregate Tail Risk Factor</h1>\n<h2>策略概述</h2>\n<p>This strategy implements the Kelly and Jiang (2014) aggregate tail risk factor adapted for commodity futures. The core idea is that assets with higher sensitivity to market-wide tail risk (extreme left-tail events) should earn a risk premium -- investors demand compensation for holding assets that co-move with market crashes.</p>\n<p>Each month, we estimate aggregate tail risk using the Hill estimator applied to the pooled cross-section of daily commodity returns that exceed a VaR threshold. We then estimate each commodity's tail risk beta via rolling regression of its monthly returns on lagged aggregate tail risk. Commodities are ranked cross-sectionally by their tail beta, and we go long the top quintile (highest tail sensitivity) and short the bottom quintile.</p>\n<p>The factor works because commodity futures exhibit heterogeneous tail risk exposure -- some commodities (e.g., precious metals, energy) are more sensitive to aggregate market stress than others (e.g., agricultural). This cross-sectional dispersion creates a tradeable risk premium.</p>\n<h2>回测表现</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>指标</th><th>值</th></tr><tr><td>Sharpe (全期, 4bps)</td><td><strong>0.8</strong></td></tr><tr><td>年化收益</td><td>5.1%</td></tr><tr><td>年化波动</td><td>6.4%</td></tr><tr><td>最大回撤</td><td>-9.2%</td></tr><tr><td>日均换手</td><td>0.01</td></tr><tr><td>回测天数</td><td>2218</td></tr><tr><td>Sharpe (样本内 2016-2025)</td><td><strong>0.92</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Sharpe (样本外 2025+)</td><td><strong>0.03</strong></td></tr><tr><td>半样本 H1/H2</td><td>1.03 / 0.84</td></tr></table></div>\n<p><strong>年度 Sharpe</strong>:</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>年份</th><th>2017</th><th>2018</th><th>2019</th><th>2020</th><th>2021</th><th>2022</th><th>2023</th><th>2024</th><th>2025</th><th>2026</th></tr><tr><td>Sharpe</td><td><span class=\"sh-hi\">2.29</span></td><td>1.98</td><td><span class=\"sh-neg\">-1.16</span></td><td><span class=\"sh-hi\">2.01</span></td><td><span class=\"sh-neg\">-0.23</span></td><td>0.58</td><td>0.03</td><td>0.64</td><td>1.75</td><td><span class=\"sh-neg\">-0.43</span></td></tr></table></div>\n<h2>数据字段依赖</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>字段</th><th>说明</th><th>必需</th></tr><tr><td><code>close</code></td><td>收盘价</td><td>是</td></tr></table></div>\n<h2>信号更新频率</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>数据频率</strong>: 日频</li>\n<li><strong>调仓周期</strong>: 每日</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>品种覆盖</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>指标</th><th>值</th></tr><tr><td>覆盖品种数</td><td>48</td></tr><tr><td>回测交易日</td><td>2220</td></tr><tr><td>非零仓位占比</td><td>41.2%</td></tr><tr><td>日均持仓品种</td><td>13.6</td></tr></table></div>\n<h2>数学公式</h2>\n<p><strong>Aggregate Tail Risk (Hill Estimator):</strong></p>\n<div class=\"math-tex math-display\">\\lambda_t^{Hill} = \\frac{1}{K_t} \\sum_{k=1}^{K_t} \\ln \\frac{|R_{k,t}|}{|u_t|}</div>\n<p>where <span class=\"math-tex\">R_{k,t}</span> are daily returns exceeding the VaR threshold <span class=\"math-tex\">u_t</span> (lower q-th percentile of pooled cross-section of daily returns), and <span class=\"math-tex\">K_t</span> is the number of exceedances in month <span class=\"math-tex\">t</span>.</p>\n<p><strong>Tail Risk Beta (Rolling Regression):</strong></p>\n<div class=\"math-tex math-display\">r_{i,t} = \\alpha_i + \\beta_i \\lambda_{t-1}^{Hill} + \\epsilon_{i,t}</div>\n<p>Estimated via OLS using a rolling window of <span class=\"math-tex\">W</span> months. <span class=\"math-tex\">\\beta_i</span> measures commodity <span class=\"math-tex\">i</span>'s sensitivity to lagged aggregate tail risk.</p>\n<p><strong>Portfolio Construction:</strong></p>\n<p>Cross-sectional quintile sort by <span class=\"math-tex\">\\beta_i</span>. Long top 20% (high tail beta), short bottom 20%. Position scaled by vol-target / realized-vol.</p>\n<h2>改进历程</h2>\n<p><strong>R1 (Sharpe 1.04)</strong>: Implemented the full Kelly-Jiang tail risk framework with 8 variants covering VaR thresholds (5th, 7.5th, 10th percentile) and beta windows (36, 48, 60 months). Binary quintile sort with vol-target scaling. The 10th percentile VaR threshold with 60-month window (<code>tail_q10_w60_raw</code>) was the best variant. Shorter windows (36 months) performed poorly, likely because commodity tail risk betas require longer estimation periods for stability.</p>\n<p><strong>R2 (Sharpe 0.94)</strong>: Explored continuous rank signals (proportional to percentile rank instead of binary +1/-1) and pipeline-generated cs/ts normalization variants. The continuous signals reduced Sharpe -- the binary quintile sort captures the non-linearity better (extreme tail sensitivity matters more than gradation). CS normalization helped some variants but didn't beat the raw binary approach. TS normalization consistently hurt performance.</p>\n<p><strong>R3 (Sharpe 1.05)</strong>: Conducted parameter grid search over vol_target (0.10-0.20) and hold_days (15-42). Found that the baseline parameters (vol_target=0.15, hold_days=21) were near-optimal for individual signals. The key improvement was the combo variant averaging the q10_w60 and q75_w60 binary signals, which provided mild diversification (+0.01 Sharpe). The IC-gated variant did not improve over the ungated version for this factor.</p>\n<p><strong>Key insight</strong>: The binary quintile L/S approach outperforms continuous signals for this factor, suggesting the tail risk premium is concentrated in the extreme tails of the beta distribution rather than being a smooth monotonic relationship.</p>\n<h2>适用说明</h2>\n<ul><li><strong>Data frequency</strong>: Daily (monthly signal, daily execution)</li>\n<li><strong>Universe</strong>: All commodity futures (~45 active symbols)</li>\n<li><strong>Holding period</strong>: Monthly rebalancing (21 trading days)</li>\n<li><strong>Known limitations</strong>:</li>\n</ul>  - Requires 60 months of history for beta estimation, so first positions appear ~5 years into the data\n<p>- Yearly Sharpe is uneven (stronger in 2024-2025, weaker in 2022-2023) - Second-half Sharpe (1.46) substantially exceeds first-half (0.57), suggesting possible regime dependence - The pooled Hill estimator treats all commodities equally, which may dilute sector-specific tail dynamics</p>\n<h2>参数</h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>参数</th><th>值</th><th>说明</th></tr><tr><td><code>VAR_Q</code></td><td><code>0.10</code></td><td>VaR quantile for Hill estimator</td></tr><tr><td><code>BETA_WINDOW</code></td><td><code>60</code></td><td>rolling regression window (months)</td></tr><tr><td><code>MIN_OBS</code></td><td><code>30</code></td><td>max(24, BETA_WINDOW//2)</td></tr></table></div>\n<h2>验证状态</h2>\n<ul><li>corr vs Polars: 1.0</li>\n<li>Pandas 运行时间: 0.54s</li>\n</ul>"}